To reuse the same `SetUp()` function with a negative test case, you can consider making use of parameterized tests provided by Google Test. Parameterized tests allow you to run the same test code multiple times with different inputs and expected outputs. In your case, you can have a parameterized test where you can pass different input values to the `SetUp()` function. 

Here's an example of how you can write a parameterized test with negative test cases:

1. Define a struct to hold the test data:

```cpp
struct TestData {
    int count;
    point* points;
};

class NaviProcessTri : public ::testing::TestWithParam<TestData> {
 protected:
    contour* testContour;
    contour* testResult;
    void SetUp() override {
        testContour = new contour;
        testResult = new contour;
        TestData data = GetParam();
        testContour->count = data.count;
        testContour->p = data.points;
        testResult->p = NULL;
        testResult->count = 0;
    }

    void TearDown() override {
        delete[] testContour->p;
        delete testContour;
        delete[] testResult->p;
        delete testResult;
    }
};
```

2. Define your parameterized tests:

```cpp
TEST_P(NaviProcessTri, NegativeTest)
{
    int ret = process_triangles(testContour, testResult);
    ASSERT_EQ(ret, -1); // Assuming -1 indicates an error in the process_triangles function
    // You can add more assertions based on the specific requirements of your negative test case
}

INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P(NegativeTestCases, NaviProcessTri, testing::Values(
    TestData{0, nullptr},  // Test case with count 0 and null points
    TestData{2, new point[2]{{1,1}, {2,2}}},  // Test case with count 2 and specific points
    // Add more test data as needed
));
```

In this setup, the `NaviProcessTri` class is now a parameterized test fixture that takes `TestData` as a parameter. The `SetUp()` function initializes the test data based on the parameters passed to the test case.

You can define different negative test cases by providing different test data in the `INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P` macro. This way, you can reuse the same `SetUp()` function for multiple negative test cases with different input values.

