In order to use the `INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P` macro for parameterized tests in Google Test, you need to include the appropriate header file. The `INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P` macro is defined in the `gmock/gmock-generated-nice-strict.h` header file, so you need to include this header file in your test file to use this macro.

Here is the proper way to include the necessary headers to use the `INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P` macro for parameterized tests in Google Test:

```cpp
#include <gtest/gtest.h>  // Header for Google Test framework
#include <gmock/gmock-generated-nice-strict.h>  // Header for INSTANTIATE_TEST_CASE_P macro

// Include other necessary headers for your test cases
```

By including `gtest/gtest.h` and `gmock/gmock-generated-nice-strict.h`, you will have access to the Google Test framework and the macros required for defining parameterized tests and instantiating them with custom test data. Make sure to replace `'gmock/gmock-generated-nice-strict.h'` with the correct path to the header file in your project setup if it is located elsewhere.

To write both positive and negative test cases using `TEST_F` without using parameterized tests, you can define separate test functions within the same test fixture class (`NaviProcessTri`) and structure them to cover both positive and negative scenarios. Here is an example of how you can achieve this:

```cpp
class NaviProcessTri : public ::testing::Test {
protected:
    contour* testContour;
    contour* testResult;

    void SetUp() override {
        testContour = new contour;
        testResult = new contour;
        testContour->count = 4;
        testContour->p = new point[4]{{1,1}, {2,1}, {1,2}, {0,0}}; // Set up initial test data
        testResult->p = NULL;
        testResult->count = 0;
    }

    void TearDown() override {
        delete[] testContour->p;
        delete testContour;
        delete[] testResult->p;
        delete testResult;
    }
};

// Positive test case
TEST_F(NaviProcessTri, processTri_Positive) {
    int ret = process_triangles(testContour, testResult);
    ASSERT_EQ(ret, 1); // Assuming 1 indicates successful processing
    ASSERT_EQ(testResult->count, 3); // Assuming 3 is the expected count
}

// Negative test case
TEST_F(NaviProcessTri, processTri_Negative) {
    // Modify test data to create a negative scenario
    testContour->count = 0; // Test data with invalid count
    testContour->p = nullptr; // Test data with NULL points

    int ret = process_triangles(testContour, testResult);
    ASSERT_EQ(ret, -1); // Assuming -1 indicates an error in the process_triangles function
    // Add more negative assertions if needed
}
```

In this setup, we define two separate test functions within the `NaviProcessTri` test fixture class. The `SetUp` function is used to set up the initial test data, and the `TearDown` function performs cleanup after each test. The positive test case (`processTri_Positive`) tests the successful processing scenario, while the negative test case (`processTri_Negative`) tests a scenario where an error is expected.

By structuring the test cases in this way, you can write both positive and negative test cases within the same test fixture using the `TEST_F` macro, making it easier to manage and organize the test scenarios.

